<br>
Several weeks ago, the school forced us all to go to work experience (translation: slave labour), and I worked under a cartoonist at the local newspaper for a week. When he saw me drawing manga style, he told me that the sooner I stop drawing that style, the better.<br>
<br>
He explained to me that manga/anime does not have a very big following here in Australia, and you have to be into it to understand it, therefore it is better (and no doubt more profitable) to stick to the Western way of cartooning/drawing. (Though I couldn't get my hand to make the shapes required when he gave me a fifty-four year old book on how to draw stuff like Bugs Bunny -_-<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So tell me, what's the market for manga like? Is it really that unpopular? (Not really intrested in how popular it is in the US- I don't live there. I'd like something a bit more relevant ^_^)<br>
<br>
~Friezaess <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ukagebu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kagebu</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/22/02 7:31:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1900.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://liquid2k.com/datenshidojo/sano01.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The market for manga</span><hr size=1> Manga in the U.S. isn't as popular as anime in the U.S is. I don't even think one person at my new school knws what manga is, yet alot of them watch the &quot;anime&quot; on Cartoon network.<br>
<br>
Manga is still fairly popular, and with the Shonen jump magazine making its appearance in the U.S. I'm sure when word gets out that it wil become a big hit. I don't know about Australia, but it seems that they are pretty far behind (Some people told me that they don't get video games that are recently released in america until a few months later, or even years.)<br>
<br>
I think its pretty damned stupid for the newspaper guy to tell you to stop drawing in manga style, because I'm sure that people would enjoy it (it isn't that different from western style. What's wrong with that guy?) <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ukagebu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kagebu</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0> at: 8/22/02 7:32:43 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uhcomiku.showPublicProfile?language=EN>HComiku</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(10/6/02 4:42:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1900.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.h-comiku.com/hcban3.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The market for manga</span><hr size=1> The market for anime and manga is growing everyday, here in the United States, and world wide for that matter.  Just look at this English speaking board for example.  Soon there is going to be a big demand for the style you are drawing, by the audience that is currently consuming it.  Look at the afternoon cartoon schedule, it's 90% anime.  When was the last time an American cartoon series last more than 1 series, and don't bring Cartoon Network into this, because their stuff is recycled, hackeny garbage. My advice is stick with it, because Bugs Bunny died with Chuck Jones, Snoopy died with Charles Schulz, Disney died with Walt, and Felix died with Max Fleischer.  Osamu Tezuka, however, died giving birth to the revolution of manga, and is now known as &quot;manga no kamisama' or 'God of Manga'.  The day of the Western cartoonist is on it's last leg, and you need to help kick that cripple on it's back.<br>
Keep on Keepin' on <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uwithroo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Withroo</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_purplespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(10/6/02 7:39:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1900.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpost.net/wi/withroo/haru.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The market for manga</span><hr size=1> Even if the anime genre is growing every day, manga is a bit slower on the uptake, since most North Americans (no idea about the Europeans, though I think manga's more known to them than us) favour the bang-em-up action to just reading. These days, actual reading is growing a bit unpopular.<br>
<br>
As for future growth in popularity, it won't happen until a good lot of the slightly-older-than-12 folks field interest. This won't happen if the current rate of &quot;Whaat? Real-life implications of nastiness! Heck no! Scrub, cut, edit!! Must not let little children know of the thing called 'reality'! Don't wanna lose money to them suing lazy parents who poke fingers instead of taking the matters of raising their kiddies to their own hands!&quot; going on.<br>
<br>
Once that barrier of &quot;keep the kiddies behind the rose-coloured glass&quot; is lept (i.e. accept the reality and rising culture), popularity will indeed grow.<br>
<br>
Another remaining barrier is the culture differences that are constantly edited out. Sadly, majority of westerners are idiots who won't bother to deal with anything different from what they presently have (and they think everyone else is the same way), so they change the original to what they're used to. I've lost count on how many times I've had to explain to friends about the Asian culture references (riceballs, onsens, the bowing, Shintoism, some aspects of Buddhism, etc.) in many unedited anime and manga.<br>
<br>
Pretty much, it ends up with the editors and producers deciding to leave in everything, so it piques interest and awareness in anyone with curiousity. Then bang, we've got culture awareness, instead of the typical live-under-rock-and-meddle approach NA has right now.<br>
<br>
As for your present predicament, you can stick to your present style to increase awareness in your own way, but be warned, it's not going to be easy at all. Speaking from the perspective of just an observer (and a motley lecturing from Common Sense), it's best you take another job along with the chosen career of manga-styledom, just in case.<br>
<br>
To note, western style won't die out. It's too deeply rooted into THIS side of the Pacific. It'll evolve in itself over the years, as will anime and manga. Ideally, there would be the two sides on balance, with much arguing against each other from both sides (can't escape that; it's human nature to bicker and quibble over who's superior). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/utempted2rule.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tempted2Rule</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(10/6/02 7:47:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1900.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The market for manga</span><hr size=1> Haha Quote &quot;it's human nature to bicker and quibble over who's superior&quot; too true, bleh y do i gotta be human... we're so pathetic lol<br>
